{"cursor":"6156","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In graph theory, a 'cut' is a partition of the vertices of a graph into two\ndisjoint subsets. The 'cut-set' of the cut is the set of edges whose end points\nare in different subsets of the partition. Edges are said to be crossing the cut\nif they are in its cut-set.\n\nIn an unweighted undirected graph, the size or weight of a cut is the number of\nedges crossing the cut. In a weighted graph, the same term is defined by the sum\nof the weights of the edges crossing the cut.\n\nIn a flow network, an 's-t cut' is a cut that requires the ''source'' and the\n''sink'' to be in different subsets, and its cut-set only consists of edges\ngoing from the source's side to the sink's side. The capacity of an s-t cut is\ndefined by the sum of capacity of each edge in the cut-set.\n\nThe cut of a graph can sometimes refer to its cut-set instead of the partition.\n","linknr":160,"url":"Cut_(graph_theory)","recorded":1362674371,"links":23,"instances":["graph_theory","graph_theory"],"pdf":["http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~odonnell/papers/maxcut.pdf","http://www.ic.unicamp.br/~fkm/publication/Rairo11.pdf","http://www.ic.unicamp.br/~fkm/publication/Rairo11.pdf"],"categories":["Graph connectivity","Combinatorial optimization"],"headings":["Definition","Minimum cut","Maximum cut","Sparsest cut","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/e/6/3e624cd0f7dc2ae10fb0ac1fafd5bab1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/0/5206560a306a2e085a437fd258eb57ce.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/e/9/9e9992d6bf50b7580f971487c466a8cb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/e/6/3e624cd0f7dc2ae10fb0ac1fafd5bab1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/f/9/1f91c52f1a198771670ab18fed186555.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/d/9/8d9c307cb7f3c4a32822a51922d1ceaa.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/1/5/a15fda5331218e41f76a749880c5c2f8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/a/5/5a580b07cd6a1ab7e4e4d0647b3010d5.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/mat